Date: Wed 19 Sep 2001 21:51:54 -0400
From: Brenda Ward <wardbg@excite.com>
Source: Memphis and Shelby County Health Department, press release,
Mon 17
Sep 2001 [edited


First West Nile Virus-positive Birds Reported in Tennessee
----------------------------------------------------------
Yvonne Madlock, Director, Memphis and Shelby County Health
Department, announced today that the Tennessee Department of Health
laboratory in Nashville has identified through preliminary testing, 9
birds recently found in Shelby County to be positive for West Nile
virus (WNV). The birds have been sent to the Centers for Disease
Control & Prevention (CDC) laboratory in Fort Collins, Colorado for
confirmatory testing. They are the first birds to test positive for
West Nile virus in Tennessee.
No human cases of the WNV have been reported to date in Tennessee.
These birds were dead Blue Jays found in zip codes 38117 and 38119.
Memphis and Shelby County Health Department plans to increase
larviciding and surveillance activities in these zip codes. While
adulticiding ("spraying") is not as effective in controlling
mosquitoes as larvaciding, the Department will begin adulticiding in
these areas early Tuesday morning.
Since the beginning of the mosquito season, in early April 2001, the
Health Department's Vector Control Program has worked to reduce
mosquito breeding throughout Shelby County with the aggressive
elimination of mosquitoes by extensive application of larvicide to
sites of standing water that cannot be emptied or drained. Daily
monitoring of mosquitoes in the city and county has been conducted by
collecting mosquito larvae and adult mosquitoes to help the Department
to determine the distribution, density and type of mosquitoes in our
community.
--
Brenda Ward
<wardbg@excite.com>
